The white figure with his skull-like head drowsing on the high throne looks to me like a seer or prophet, the incense lulling him into trance. The dark crowd of hooded men wait in tense expectation for the seer's words, and the tension between Earth and Heaven, mundane and mystery, is palpable in the set faces and stiff silence of the crowd, the whiteness of the seer and the blackness of the men. The seer looks about to speak at any moment, excitement barely held at bay.
The smooth, sloping lines of the throne and the plume of smoke illuminate the smoothness of this leader and the power he/she has over people.
The sinister man on the throne inspires awe and respect while the black and white theme adds drama.

So much to see in this piece I am overwhelmed. The skiers in the center first caught my eyes as they look like they are suspended in a winter paradise. The white lines give the illusion of snow, and the stick drawings could easily be snow-covered fir branches. There is snow, dancing, color, and movement all on a pitch-black canvas. There is a couple dancing in the upper left. The kneeling figures in the upper center could be proposing marriage, or just sitting on a blue blanket. It is unclear what the figures to the left of the skiers are doing, but with the one in the red jacket holding the pale figure down, it gives the green figure access to the pale one's bottom. There is a disturbing image in the right lower corner where a woman in white floats above a red structure resembling an altar. Is she to be a sacrifice? Green shoots and red berries are pushing up underneath. The icy pond in the left foreground gives a sense of stillness and balance, but this is easily overlooked.
